(appendix
  :book \"book-of-motion\"
  :number 4
  :title \"UPA and Animated Modernism\"
  :short-title \"upa-modernism\"
  :estimated-words 1400
  :subject-verified \"United Productions of America (UPA), founded 1943 by former studio animators including John Hubley, Zachary Schwartz, David Hilberman, and others.\"
  :philosopher-weave (wittgenstein-late jung aristotle)

  :prose
\"United Productions of America — universally called UPA — was founded in 1943 by a group of animators who had been working at various American studios and wanted to make animation that looked and moved differently. Over the following fifteen years, UPA developed a house style that broke with the naturalistic character animation of the feature-studio tradition and produced some of the most influential short films of the 1950s. When historians of animation talk about *modernism* in the medium, they usually mean UPA.

# What UPA looked like

Imagine a mid-century magazine illustration or a graphic-designed poster. Flat colored areas rather than rendered shading. Bold outlines. Angular characters with stylized proportions. Backgrounds that suggest space rather than depicting it fully — a suggestion of a wall, a chair rendered as a few lines, a floor implied by a colored plane.

That is what UPA films looked like. They were graphic design in motion.

The stylization was not just a look. It was tied to a philosophy of animation. UPA's animators believed that the naturalistic character animation of the feature studios was a wrong turn — that trying to make animated characters look and move like *real people* was missing what animation could uniquely do. Animation, they argued, was drawing that moved. Its power was in stylization, in graphic design, in visual invention. Making it look like live-action was not using its unique strengths.

# The house style

UPA films had several distinctive stylistic markers:

**Limited animation.** Characters didn't fully-animate the way Termite Terrace and studio-feature characters did. Instead of drawing every frame with all body parts moving, UPA animators would hold much of the body still and animate only the specific parts required for the current action. A talking character might have only their mouth animated; a walking character might have only their legs.

This was partly a budget decision — limited animation is cheaper — but it was also an aesthetic choice. Held drawings looked graphic, poster-like. Focused animation drew the eye to the specific action.

**Flat backgrounds.** No rendered depth, no atmospheric perspective. Backgrounds were graphic designs. Characters existed in front of flat colored planes.

**Stylized character design.** Characters had strong graphic silhouettes but were not naturalistic. Angular geometries; caricatured proportions; simplified anatomy.

**Modernist score.** UPA films often used contemporary jazz or modernist classical music rather than the Wagnerian orchestral scores of feature animation or the Stalling quotational medleys of Warner shorts.

# The major films

*Gerald McBoing-Boing* (1950). Directed by Robert Cannon (or Bobe Cannon as he was called). Based on a Dr. Seuss story. A little boy named Gerald can only speak in sound effects rather than words. The design is deliberately stylized and the animation is limited. The film won the Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film in 1950.

*Rooty Toot Toot* (1951). Directed by John Hubley. An animated adaptation of the *Frankie and Johnny* murder ballad, set in a courtroom. Fast, angular, jazz-scored. Bold color choices — pinks, blacks, oranges. One of the most stylistically radical animated shorts of its era.

*The Tell-Tale Heart* (1953). Directed by Ted Parmelee. An animated adaptation of the Poe story. Voiced by James Mason. Dark, expressionist, deeply stylized backgrounds evoking mental disturbance rather than physical space. Nominated for the Academy Award.

*Boyhood Daze* (1957). Directed by Chuck Jones during a UPA-adjacent period. Uses UPA-derived stylization within a Warner narrative context.

*Mr. Magoo* series (starting 1949). The near-sighted Mr. Magoo character was UPA's most commercially successful creation. The shorts used UPA's stylized approach applied to a comic character. The character's blind-man premise has been widely criticized in later decades as insensitive; the design work and animation, however, remain historically significant.

# The influence on graphic design and animation

UPA's stylistic vocabulary influenced not just animation but American commercial art of the 1950s and 1960s. UPA's work overlapped with the mid-century modern movement in graphic design, illustration, and animation for television commercials. Many of the animators who worked at UPA moved into commercial work in the late 1950s, taking the UPA style with them, and mid-century American animated commercials often bear a strong UPA family resemblance.

Later animation-modernism traditions — including some contemporary independent animators and various television animation styles — trace back to UPA. The show *The Simpsons* in its early years shows some UPA influence in its flat color palettes and stylized character design. The direct visual descendants are numerous.

# What UPA teaches us

The UPA lesson is that animation does not have to try to look real. It can be graphic. It can be stylized. It can hold drawings for longer than continuous motion requires, letting each drawing read as a composition on its own. It can use bold colors, flat planes, angular geometries.

For an animator working today, UPA is one alternative to full-animation naturalism. If your project is a graphic-design piece — a title sequence, a short animated illustration, a music video — the UPA vocabulary may be a better fit than trying to produce feature-quality character animation on a small budget. The choice of style is aesthetic, and UPA proves that stylization can be as expressive as naturalism.

# What we can do in Scheme

Let's build a small UPA-style scene: limited animation, flat background, held poses.

```scheme
;; UPA-style scene: a character speaks. Only the mouth animates.
;; The body is a graphic design in a colored area.

(define (upa-character-still)
  ;; Draw once and hold
  (world/background 'salmon)                           ; flat colored background
  (world/place-shape 'rectangle 100 200 200 300 'olive)  ; simple furniture
  (world/place-figure 'stylized 250 200 'stiff-body)   ; angular figure
  (world/set-eye-position 250 220 'looking-right))

(define (animate-mouth frame)
  ;; The only animation: the mouth opening and closing
  (let ((mouth-open? (odd? (quotient frame 6))))
    (if mouth-open?
        (world/set-mouth 250 240 'open)
        (world/set-mouth 250 240 'closed))))

(define (upa-scene)
  ;; Draw the character once. Hold. Animate only the mouth.
  (upa-character-still)
  (for-each
    (lambda (f)
      (animate-mouth f)
      (world/render!)
      (world/wait (/ 1.0 24.0)))
    (range 0 96)))    ; four seconds
```

The character is drawn once. The background is flat. The only motion is a mouth opening and closing every quarter-second or so. This is limited animation in the UPA sense: a graphic composition that moves just enough to indicate speech.

The result reads as UPA-style. Compare with feature-studio-style animation, which would have the character breathing, blinking, gesturing, shifting weight — many secondary motions layered over the primary action. UPA strips all of that away and lets the pose be the composition.

# Recommended viewing

*Gerald McBoing-Boing* (1950). Academy Award winner. Available on many streaming services and DVD compilations.

*Rooty Toot Toot* (1951). Cornerstone of animated modernism.

*The Tell-Tale Heart* (1953). Adaptation of Poe as expressionist animation.

Any of Amid Amidi's compiled UPA shorts collections on DVD.

# Sources cited

Amid Amidi, *Cartoon Modern: Style and Design in Fifties Animation* (Chronicle Books, 2006).

Adam Abraham, *When Magoo Flew: The Rise and Fall of Animation Studio UPA* (Wesleyan UP, 2012).

Michael Frierson, 'The Animation Aesthetic of UPA,' in *A Reader in Animation Studies*, ed. Jayne Pilling (John Libbey, 1997).\"

  :notes
\"UPA founding date (1943) and founders (Hubley, Schwartz, Hilberman among others) are standard. Named films (Gerald McBoing-Boing, Rooty Toot Toot, The Tell-Tale Heart, Boyhood Daze, Mr. Magoo series) are all verifiable with their years and directors. The critique of Mr. Magoo's premise as later-considered-insensitive is a widely-noted fact in animation-history scholarship, not a judgment invented here.\"

  :philosopher-weave-details
\"Wittgenstein-late: UPA style as language-game — a set of conventions the audience learned to read as its own aesthetic, distinct from naturalistic animation.
Jung: stylization as archetype — the flat graphic body reads as a category rather than an individual, which is a different mode of character.
Aristotle: limited animation as economy — the parts moved are exactly the parts required for the action, no more.\"

  :tie-forward
\"Appendix 5 will move to Studio Ghibli — the Japanese hand-drawn feature tradition that carried a different sensibility into the twenty-first century.\")
")
